<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="tmux-power-user">
  <metadata>
    <tier>solo</tier>
    <group>infra</group>
    <domain>server-craft</domain>
    <summary>tmux configuration for remote dev: Ctrl+A prefix, mouse/vi-mode, pane/window navigation, TPM plugins (resurrect/continuum), status bar with metrics, session templates.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>tmux</tag>
      <tag>terminal</tag>
      <tag>multiplexing</tag>
      <tag>session-management</tag>
      <tag>remote-work</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-26</created>
  </metadata>
  <content>
    <title>tmux Power User</title>
    <summary>Master tmux for remote development: configure prefix (Ctrl+A), enable mouse and vi-mode, set up intuitive pane/window navigation, install plugins (resurrect/continuum) for session persistence, customize the status bar with system metrics, and build session templates for parallel project workflows.</summary>
    <why>
      <p>For a solo developer on a remote server, tmux is the foundation of productivity: sessions survive SSH disconnections, multiple panes enable simultaneous log-watching and code editing, and plugins (resurrect/continuum) auto-save/restore sessions across reboots. Without it, every reconnect means rebuilding context from scratch.</p>
    </why>
    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Developer works primarily over SSH and needs persistent sessions</item>
        <item>Running multiple concurrent AI agent sessions that must stay live without supervision</item>
        <item>Building a named-session workflow where each project has a dedicated tmux session</item>
        <item>Setting up a monitoring dashboard with persistent panes (htop, logs, docker stats)</item>
        <item>Scripting session layouts that an agent or cron job can create/restore</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>
    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Local-only workstation development where an IDE terminal suffices</item>
        <item>Ephemeral CI/CD environments (tmux adds no value in non-interactive pipelines)</item>
        <item>Containerized deployments where the process is PID 1</item>
        <item>Terminals that do not support 256-color or proper escape sequences</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="prefix-key-and-basics">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use Ctrl+A as the prefix key rather than the default Ctrl+B; it is more ergonomic and consistent with GNU screen muscle memory.</statement>
        <rationale>Ctrl+B requires moving the left hand off the home row. Ctrl+A is reachable without moving the hand, reducing friction across hundreds of daily prefix-chord invocations.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Set base-index 1 and pane-base-index 1; the default zero-indexing makes Alt+1 select window 0, which feels counter-intuitive.</statement>
        <rationale>With base-index 1, Alt+1 through Alt+9 map directly to the visual position of windows in the status bar.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always set escape-time to 10ms or less; the default 500ms causes a noticeable delay in vim when pressing Escape.</statement>
        <rationale>Vim and other editors rely on fast Escape detection. The default 500ms makes modal editing feel sluggish over SSH.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Essential tmux.conf configuration">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Prefix: Ctrl+A (ergonomic, screen-compatible muscle memory)
set -g prefix C-a
unbind C-b
bind C-a send-prefix

# Enable full mouse (scroll, click panes, resize, select text)
set -g mouse on

# Vi mode for copy (Escape-free text selection in scroll buffer)
setw -g mode-keys vi
bind -T copy-mode-vi v send-keys -X begin-selection
bind -T copy-mode-vi y send-keys -X copy-selection-and-cancel

# 1-based indexing for intuitive Alt+number window switching
set -g base-index 1
setw -g pane-base-index 1
set -g renumber-windows on

# Faster escape for vim
set -sg escape-time 10
set -g focus-events on

# Large scrollback
set -g history-limit 50000
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="splits-and-navigation">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use | and - for splits; the defaults &quot; and % are not mnemonic. Open splits in the current pane's working directory.</statement>
        <rationale>| visually represents a vertical divider (horizontal split). - represents a horizontal line (vertical split). Both are immediately memorable. Current-path inheritance eliminates the need to cd after each split.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Intuitive split bindings and navigation">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Intuitive splits that inherit the current directory
bind | split-window -h -c "#{pane_current_path}"
bind - split-window -v -c "#{pane_current_path}"
unbind '"'
unbind %

# New window in current directory
bind c new-window -c "#{pane_current_path}"

# Pane navigation without prefix (Ctrl+arrows)
bind -n C-Up    select-pane -U
bind -n C-Down  select-pane -D
bind -n C-Left  select-pane -L
bind -n C-Right select-pane -R

# Pane resize with prefix + H/J/K/L (vi directions)
bind -r H resize-pane -L 5
bind -r J resize-pane -D 5
bind -r K resize-pane -U 5
bind -r L resize-pane -R 5

# Window switching with Alt+number (no prefix needed)
bind -n M-1 select-window -t 1
bind -n M-2 select-window -t 2
bind -n M-3 select-window -t 3
bind -n M-4 select-window -t 4
bind -n M-5 select-window -t 5

# Reload config without restarting tmux
bind r source-file ~/.tmux.conf \; display "Config reloaded"
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="status-bar-setup">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Run the status bar script with a 5-second refresh interval; 1-second intervals cause noticeable CPU overhead on low-power VPS instances.</statement>
        <rationale>A status bar that refreshes every second calls shell scripts 60 times per minute. At 5 seconds, the overhead drops to 12 calls per minute with no perceptible staleness for CPU/memory metrics.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Status bar configuration with system metrics">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
set -g status-position bottom
set -g status-style "bg=colour235,fg=colour248"
set -g status-interval 5

# Left: session name with color accent
set -g status-left-length 30
set -g status-left "#[fg=colour0,bg=colour4,bold] #S #[fg=colour4,bg=colour235,nobold] "

# Right: system metrics script + time
set -g status-right-length 120
set -g status-right '#(~/.tmux-system.sh) #[fg=colour240]| #[fg=colour248]%H:%M '

# Pane border colors (dim inactive, bright active)
set -g pane-border-style "fg=colour240"
set -g pane-active-border-style "fg=colour4"

# Terminal true-color support
set -g default-terminal "screen-256color"
set -ga terminal-overrides ",xterm-256color:RGB"
]]></code>
      </example>
      <reference path="templates/tmux-system.sh">Status bar script: CPU/memory/disk with color-coded thresholds</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="tpm-installation">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Install TPM before adding any plugin declarations to .tmux.conf; otherwise tmux.conf fails to source and all settings are lost.</statement>
        <rationale>TPM's run directive at the bottom of .tmux.conf initializes all plugins. If the TPM directory does not exist, the run command silently fails and no plugins load.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Installing and configuring TPM">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Install TPM (one-time, before first use)
git clone https://github.com/tmux-plugins/tpm ~/.tmux/plugins/tpm

# In .tmux.conf — declare plugins
set -g @plugin 'tmux-plugins/tpm'
set -g @plugin 'tmux-plugins/tmux-resurrect'
set -g @plugin 'tmux-plugins/tmux-continuum'

# MUST be the last line in .tmux.conf
run '~/.tmux/plugins/tpm/tpm'

# After adding plugins: press prefix + I to install
# To update: prefix + U
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="essential-plugins">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use tmux-resurrect and tmux-continuum for automatic session persistence. Enable @resurrect-capture-pane-contents so the text visible in each pane is saved and restored.</statement>
        <rationale>Without pane contents capture, a restored session shows empty panes. With it, the last visible output (logs, process output) is replayed into each pane. Continuum auto-saves every 15 minutes and auto-restores on tmux server start.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Resurrect and Continuum configuration">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
set -g @plugin 'tmux-plugins/tmux-resurrect'
set -g @plugin 'tmux-plugins/tmux-continuum'

# Resurrect: save pane content and vim session files
set -g @resurrect-capture-pane-contents 'on'
set -g @resurrect-strategy-vim 'session'

# Continuum: auto-save every 15 min, auto-restore on start
set -g @continuum-restore 'on'
set -g @continuum-save-interval '15'

# Manual save/restore commands (outside of auto):
# prefix + Ctrl+s = save
# prefix + Ctrl+r = restore
]]></code>
      </example>
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Optional: add tmux-yank for system clipboard integration over SSH, but verify xclip or xsel is installed on the remote host first.</statement>
        <rationale>tmux-yank copies to system clipboard (macOS pbcopy, Linux xclip/xsel). Over SSH, this requires xclip or xsel on the remote host.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="plugin-gotchas">
      <list>
        <item>Forgetting prefix + I after adding a new plugin declaration — plugin directories are not created until install is run</item>
        <item>TPM run directive not at the bottom of .tmux.conf — plugins declared after run do not load</item>
        <item>tmux-yank requires xclip or xsel on the remote host for SSH clipboard forwarding to work</item>
        <item>tmux-continuum auto-restore only runs when tmux server starts, not on attach; a running server will not auto-restore</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="session-commands">
      <list>
        <item>tmux new-session -d -s &lt;name&gt; — create detached named session</item>
        <item>tmux attach -t &lt;name&gt; — attach; creates session if it does not exist (with -d)</item>
        <item>tmux has-session -t &lt;name&gt; — check existence (use in scripts before attach)</item>
        <item>tmux kill-session -t &lt;name&gt; — destroy session and all its windows/panes</item>
        <item>tmux ls — list all sessions with window counts and activity times</item>
        <item>prefix + s — interactive session picker (fzf-powered with tmux-fzf plugin)</item>
        <item>prefix + d — detach from current session (session stays alive)</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="create-or-attach-pattern">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Always use has-session before creating a named session; re-running a session-creation script should attach to the existing session, not fail or create duplicates.</statement>
        <rationale>Session scripts are often called from aliases, shell startup, or agents. If the session already exists, recreating it destroys ongoing work.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Safe create-or-attach session script">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
#!/bin/bash
# Create-or-attach pattern (safe to call repeatedly)
SESSION="${1:-dev}"
DIR="${2:-$(pwd)}"

if tmux has-session -t "$SESSION" 2>/dev/null; then
    tmux attach -t "$SESSION"
    exit 0
fi

# Create new session with layout
tmux new-session -d -s "$SESSION" -c "$DIR"
tmux rename-window -t "$SESSION:1" "edit"
tmux new-window -t "$SESSION" -n "term" -c "$DIR"
tmux new-window -t "$SESSION" -n "run" -c "$DIR"
tmux split-window -h -t "$SESSION:run" -c "$DIR"
tmux select-window -t "$SESSION:1"
tmux attach -t "$SESSION"
]]></code>
      </example>
      <reference path="templates/tmux-session.sh">Generic create-or-attach session launcher</reference>
    </section>

    <section name="nested-tmux">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Use different prefix keys for local and remote tmux to avoid double-prefix confusion: Ctrl+A locally, Ctrl+B remotely (or vice versa).</statement>
        <rationale>When inside a local tmux session and SSH'd into a remote tmux, every prefix command requires sending the prefix twice (once for local tmux to ignore, once for the remote). Different prefixes eliminate this ambiguity.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Nested tmux prefix configuration">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Local ~/.tmux.conf: Ctrl+A
set -g prefix C-a

# Remote ~/.tmux.conf (on server): keep default Ctrl+B
# OR: bind a distinct key like Ctrl+B on the remote

# To send a prefix to the inner (remote) tmux:
# Press your local prefix (Ctrl+A), then Ctrl+A again to pass through
bind C-a send-prefix
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-control">
      <rule testable="true">
        <statement>Control background processes from scripts or agents via tmux send-keys to send commands and capture-pane to inspect pane output programmatically.</statement>
        <rationale>send-keys allows scripts to interact with tmux panes without requiring an interactive terminal. capture-pane enables condition-based automation (check pane output, take action).</rationale>
      </rule>
      <example type="good" title="Controlling tmux panes from scripts">
        <code lang="bash"><![CDATA[
# Send a command to a specific pane (non-interactively from a script)
tmux send-keys -t "nero:logs.0" "journalctl --user -f -u nero-core" Enter

# Capture current pane content for programmatic inspection
tmux capture-pane -t "nero:monitor.0" -p

# Check if a specific string is visible in a pane
tmux capture-pane -t "nero:monitor.0" -p | grep -q "All OK"

# Send a key sequence to a pane (e.g., Ctrl+C to stop a process)
tmux send-keys -t "nero:run.0" C-c
tmux send-keys -t "nero:run.0" "q" Enter
]]></code>
      </example>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Sending commands to tmux panes as a substitute for proper systemd service management.</description>
        <reason>tmux panes are ephemeral user-space processes. Commands sent via send-keys do not survive server reboots. Use systemd user services for persistent processes and tmux only for interactive monitoring.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/tmux.conf" purpose="Complete power-user .tmux.conf with all settings and TPM plugins"/>
      <template path="templates/tmux-system.sh" purpose="Status bar script: CPU/MEM/Disk with color-coded thresholds"/>
      <template path="templates/tmux-session.sh" purpose="Generic create-or-attach session launcher (agent-safe)"/>
    </templates>

    <see-also>
      <link href="https://github.com/tmux/tmux/wiki">tmux Wiki</link>
      <link href="https://www.man7.org/linux/man-pages/man1/tmux.1.html">tmux manual</link>
      <link href="https://github.com/tmux-plugins">tmux Plugin Managers and official plugins</link>
    </see-also>
  </content>
</methodology>
